The 2025 NFL playoffs feature 14 teams with the Denver Broncos securing the No. 1 seed in the AFC, earning a first-round bye with a 14-3 record, followed by the New England Patriots at No. 2 and the Jacksonville Jaguars at No. 3 in the AFC. The Pittsburgh Steelers locked up the AFC North and the No. 4 seed, with the Houston Texans at No. 5, Los Angeles Chargers at No. 6, and Buffalo Bills at No. 7 rounding out the AFC playoff field. In the NFC, the Seattle Seahawks clinched the No. 1 seed, and theyâ€™re joined by the Chicago Bears at No. 2 and the Philadelphia Eagles at No. 3. The NFC South winner will take the No. 4 seed (either the Carolina Panthers or Tampa Bay Buccaneers, depending on Week 18 outcomes). Below them, the San Francisco 49ers occupy the No. 5 spot, the Los Angeles Rams are No. 6, and the Green Bay Packers sit at No. 7 as the final wild-card team. All 14 teams will compete under the standard NFL playoff format with the top seed byes and wild-card matchups. 
